  <front xml:lang="en">
    <title>SAIP: Signed Agent Identity Protocol</title>
    
    <author fullname="Srećko Jovančević"
            initials="S."
            surname="Jovančević">
      <organization>SKGO, IKT Support</organization>
      <address>
        <postal>
          <street>Makedonska 22</street>
          <city>Belgrade</city>
          <code>11000</code>
          <country>Serbia</country>
        </postal>
        <email>srecko.jovancevic@skgo.org</email>
        <uri>https://github.com/sreckojovancevic</uri>
      </address>
    </author>

    <date day="3" month="April" year="2026"/>

    <area>Applications and Real-Time</area>
    <workgroup>web-bot-auth</workgroup>

    <abstract>
      <t>The modern web lacks a reliable mechanism for verifying the identity of HTTP user agents. Existing methods such as User-Agent strings and IP-based attribution are insufficient due to spoofing, shared infrastructure, and automated agents.</t>
      <t>This document specifies SAIP (Signed Agent Identity Protocol), a lightweight, opt-in mechanism for verifiable client identity at the application layer.</t>
    </abstract>
  </front>

  <middle>
    <section title="Introduction">
      <t>SAIP introduces a lightweight, opt-in mechanism for verifiable client identity at the application layer, enabling servers to distinguish between legitimate automated traffic and malicious actors.</t>
    </section>

    <section title="Problem Statement">
      <t>User-Agent strings are trivial to manipulate.</t>
      <t>IP-based filtering is unreliable for NAT users and shared infrastructure.</t>
      <t>Automated systems are frequently blocked by generic security rules.</t>
      <t>Lack of client-level identity enables abuse and spam.</t>
    </section>

    <section title="Design Goals">
      <ul spacing="normal">
        <li>Simplicity (single-header implementation)</li>
        <li>Opt-in deployment</li>
        <li>Backward compatibility</li>
        <li>Protocol-agnostic design</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section title="Protocol Overview">
      <t>SAIP defines a cryptographic identity signal transmitted via a single HTTP-style header. It supplements existing authentication systems and enables more accurate trust decisions.</t>
    </section>

    <section title="Header Format">
SAIP: id="<ID>"; alg="<ALG>"; ts="<TS>"; nonce="<NONCE>"; [pk="<PK>"]; sig="<SIG>"
]]></artwork>
    </section>

    <section title="Parameters">
      <table align="center">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Param</th>
            <th>Type</th>
            <th>Required</th>
            <th>Description</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>id</td>
            <td>String</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Logical agent identifier</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>alg</td>
            <td>String</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Algorithm identifier</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>ts</td>
            <td>Integer</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Unix timestamp</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>nonce</td>
            <td>String</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Replay protection value</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>pk</td>
            <td>Base64URL</td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>Optional public key</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>sig</td>
            <td>Base64</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Signature</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section title="Canonicalization and Signature">
id=<id>;ts=<ts>;nonce=<nonce>;method=<method>;path=<path>
]]></artwork>
      <t>The signature binds identity to a specific request to prevent replay across endpoints.</t>
    </section>

    <section title="Processing Model">
      <t>The client constructs and signs the canonical string and sends it in the SAIP header. The server reconstructs the string, verifies the signature, and applies policy decisions.</t>
    </section>

    <section title="Trust & Discovery Model">
      <t>SAIP supports two primary trust discovery patterns: stateless (key-in-header) and registry-based (using a distributed registry such as consortium blockchain, DNS-based records, or internal pre-shared keys).</t>
    </section>

    <section title="Economic Traffic Model">
      <t>SAIP shifts traffic handling from binary filtering to incentive-based classification:</t>
+-------------------+--------------+-----------+-------------------+
| Agent Category    | SAIP Status  | Trust     | Example Rate      |
|                   |              | Level     | Limit             |
+-------------------+--------------+-----------+-------------------+
| Internal Systems  | Verified     | High      | Unrestricted      |
| Known Partners    | Verified     | Medium    | 100 req/sec       |
| General Clients   | Verified     | Low       | 10 req/sec        |
| Anonymous         | None         | Minimal   | 1 req/sec         |
+-------------------+--------------+-----------+-------------------+
]]></artwork>
    </section>

    <section title="Security Considerations">
      <ul spacing="normal">
        <li>Timestamp validation (±300 seconds)</li>
        <li>Constant-time signature verification</li>
        <li>Nonce-based replay protection</li>
        <li>Strict ID validation</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section title="IANA Considerations">
      <t>This document requests registration of the "SAIP" HTTP header field in the Permanent Message Header Field Names registry.</t>
    </section>
  </middle>

